\begin{theorem}\label{thm:spi0}
We have $\phi^*=Eh^*+\delta_{{\cal N}^\perp}$. In particular, $v\in L^1$ is a shadow price of information if and only if it solves the dual problem

and the optimum value equals $-\phi(0)$. In this case, an $x\in{\cal N}$ is optimal if and only if $Eh(x)<0$ and it minimizes the function $x\mapsto h(x,\omega)-v(\omega)\cdot x$ almost surely. 
\end{theorem}

The notion of a shadow price of information first appeared in a general single period model in Rockafellar~\cite[Example~6 in Section~10]{roc74} and Rockafellar and Wets~\cite[Section~4]{rw75}. Extension to finite discrete time was given in \cite{rw76}. Continuous-time extensions have been studied in Wets~\cite{wet75}, Back and Pliska~\cite{bp87}, Davis~\cite{dav92} and Davis and Burstein~\cite{db92} under various structural assumptions. The shadow price of information has been found useful in formulating dual problems and deriving optimality condition in general parametric stochastic optimization problems; see e.g.\ \cite{rw78,bp87,bpp}. The shadow price of information is useful also in subdifferential calculus involving conditional expectations; see \cite{rw82} and Section~\ref{ssec:2} below. As a further application, we give a dual formulation of the general dynamic programming recursion from \cite{rw76} and \cite{evs76}; see Section~\ref{ssec:3}.

The main result of this paper gives new generalized sufficient conditions for the existence of a shadow price of information for the discrete time problem~\eqref{sp}. Its proof is obtained by extending the original argument of \cite{rw76} and by relaxing some of the technical assumptions made there. As already noted, we do not require the decision strategies to be essentially bounded. This allows one to establish the existence of solutions and the absence of a duality gap e.g.\ in various problems in financial mathematics; see \cite{pp12,per14b}. We also relax the assumptions made in \cite{rw76} on the normal integrand $h$.

We will denote the {\em adapted projection} of an $x\in L^\infty$ by ${\prescript{a}{}{x}}$, that is, $({\prescript{a}{}{x}})_t=E_tx_t$, where $E_t$ denotes the conditional expectation with respect to ${\cal F}_t$. We will also use the notation $x^t:=(x_0,\ldots,x_t)$.

\begin{assumption}\label{dom}
For every $z\in{\mathop{\rm dom}\nolimits} Eh\cap L^\infty$ and every $t=0,\ldots,T$, there exists $\hat z\in{\mathop{\rm dom}\nolimits} Eh\cap L^\infty$ such that $E_t z^t=\hat z^t$.
\end{assumption}

It was assumed in \cite{rw76} (conditions C and D, respectively) that the sets ${\mathop{\rm dom}\nolimits} h(\cdot,\omega)$ are closed, uniformly bounded, and ``nonanticipative'' and that there exists a $\mu\in L^1$ such that $|h(x,\omega)|\le\mu(\omega)$ for all $x\in{\mathop{\rm dom}\nolimits} h(\cdot,\omega)$. The nonanticipativity means the projection mappings $D^t(\omega):=\{x^t\,|\, x\in{\mathop{\rm dom}\nolimits} h(\cdot,\omega)\}$ are ${\cal F}_t$-measurable for all $t$. These conditions imply Assumption~\ref{dom}. Indeed, if $z\in{\mathop{\rm dom}\nolimits} Eh\cap L^\infty$, then $z^t\in D^t(\omega)$ almost surely and, by Jensen's inequality, $E_tz^t\in{\mathop{\rm dom}\nolimits} h$ almost surely as well. By the measurable selection theorem (see \cite[Corollary~14.6]{rw98}), there exists a $\hat z\in L^0$ such that $\hat z\in{\mathop{\rm dom}\nolimits} h$ and $\hat z^t=E_tz^t$ almost surely. The uniform boundedness of ${\mathop{\rm dom}\nolimits} h$ implies that $\hat z\in L^\infty$ while the upper bound $\mu$ gives $Eh(\hat z)<\infty$.



We will also use the following.

\begin{assumption}\label{suf}
There exists $\rho\in{\mathbb{R}}$ such that, for every $z\in{\mathop{\rm aff}}{\mathop{\rm dom}\nolimits} Eh\cap L^\infty$, there exists $x\in{\mathop{\rm aff}}{\mathop{\rm dom}\nolimits} Eh\cap{\cal N}^\infty$ such that $\|x-z\|\le \rho\|{\prescript{a}{}{z}}-z\|$.
\end{assumption}

Assumption~\ref{suf} holds, in particular, if ${\prescript{a}{}{z}}\in{\mathop{\rm aff}}{\mathop{\rm dom}\nolimits} Eh$ for all $z\in{\mathop{\rm aff}}{\mathop{\rm dom}\nolimits} Eh\cap L^\infty$. In the single-step case where $T=0$, this latter condition coincides with Assumption~\ref{dom}. Assumption~\ref{suf} is also implied by the {\em strict feasibility} assumption made in \cite[Theorem~2]{rw76}. Indeed, strict feasibility implies that ${\mathop{\rm dom}\nolimits} Eh$ contains an open ball so that ${\mathop{\rm aff}}{\mathop{\rm dom}\nolimits} Eh=L^\infty$. 

In order to clarify the structure and the logic of its proof, we have split our main result in two statements of independent interest, Theorems~\ref{thm:spi} and \ref{thm:drinte} below. Combining them gives the following extension of \cite[Theorem~2]{rw76}.

\begin{theorem}\label{thm:mt}
Let Assumption~\ref{dom} and \ref{suf} hold, and assume that $Eh$ is strongly continuous at a point of ${\cal N}^\infty$ relative to ${\mathop{\rm aff}}{\mathop{\rm dom}\nolimits} Eh\cap L^\infty$. Then a shadow price of information exists.
\end{theorem}

A sufficient condition for the relative continuity will be given in Theorem~\ref{thm:rinte} below. It is obtained by extending the argument in the proof of \cite[Theorem~2]{roc71}.













